0–1445":"1370–1445","1301–Male":"1301–Deceased","1303–Female":"1303–Deceased","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1303":"1303","1445":"1445","1434":"1434","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","about 1328":"about 1328","1453":"1453","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","St Germans Society of Friends, Cornwall, England":"St Germans Society of Friends, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moyle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish: probably a nickname from Middle Cornish <i>mōl</i> ‘bald’, though its development to <i>Moyl(e)</i> is irregular.","Welsh: nickname from <i>moel</i> ‘bare, bald’, equivalent to Middle Cornish <i>mōl</i> (see 1 above).","English: variant of   Mule   or   Moule  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mule","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Vito, Angelo, Antonio, Matteo, Sal, Carmelo, Concetta, Francesco, Gaetano, Gaspare, Gino, Rosario.","English: nickname, perhaps for a stubborn person, from Middle English <i>mule</i>, <i>muel</i>, <i>meul</i>, <i>moile</i> ‘mule’ (Old French <i>mule</i>). See also   Moyle   and   Moule  , with which this name may have been interchangeable.","French: nickname from <i>mule</i> ‘female mule’."]},{"name":"Milne","meanings":["Scottish (mainly Aberdeenshire and Angus): occupational name from Middle English <i>milne</i> ‘mill’, also found as <i>mulne</i> in south and western England and <i>melne</i> in southeastern England. The Scottish name has been established in Ireland since the early 18th century, and has absorbed some cases of Irish   Moyle  . Compare   Mill   1."]},{"name":"Moyles","meanings":["English: variant of   Moyle  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: in Devon and Cornwall probably a variant of   Mullis  .","Irish (Mayo and Meath): variant of   Miles  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":0,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":9,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":54,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Moyle was born about 1328, in St Germans Society of Friends, Cornwall, England, his father, Roger Moyle, was 28 and his mother, Mrs. Roger Moyle, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Amy Langston."},"et":{"about 1328–De